Analyzing health index by behavioral and environmental characteristics of U.S. counties¶

Adelyn Chen
Prepared for Univ. of Pennsylvania Wharton - STAT 477
Professor Richard Waterman
March 16, 2022

Key Questions¶

  1. Which predictors are most strongly associated with a county's health index?
  2. Will behavioral and/or environmental health characteristics better account for the variation in county health index than simply those predictors that are most strongly correlated with the health index?
  3. On a broader scale, how well can these characteristics predict the county's health index?
  4. Given the structure of the data and models, are linear regression models or trees more effective in accounting for variation?

Dependent Variable: Health Index¶

  • This data is presented as the proportion of people in a county who have poor health.
  • Lower proportions indicate a healthier county, and vice versa.
  • Below is a histogram of the health indices across all counties.
In [354]:
sns.displot(county_data['Poor.Health'], kde=True);

Distribution of Health Index¶

  • Roughly right skewed
  • Mean of 0.174
    • On average, 17.4% of residents in a county have poor health.

Notable Locations¶

  • 4 of the 5 healthiest counties are concentrated in the Central U.S. (Colorado, Kansas, South Dakota (2)), and the remaining county is in Connecticut.
  • 4 of the 5 unhealthiest counties are in Texas.

Health Index by State¶

  • Although only one of the top 5 healthiest counties is in Connecticut, on average Connecticut is the healthiest state.
  • By contrast, although 4 of the 5 unhealthiest counties are in Texas, on average Texas is only the 12th unhealthiest state.

Linear Regression Models¶

We will run 3 linear regression models for comparison; for simplicity, the actual regression outputs have been omitted. All included predictors are continuous.

Model 1: Correlated Predictors¶

  • Log of Median Household Income
  • Excessive Drinking

Model 2: Behavioral Health Determinants¶

  • Adult Obesity
  • Proportion of Smokers
  • High School Graduation
  • Insufficient Sleep
  • Physical Inactivity
  • Excessive Drinking

Model 3: Environmental Health Determinants¶

  • Median Household Income (we will continue to use the log)
  • Severe Housing Problems
  • Unemployment

Model Metric Comparison¶

Model # Characteristics R-squared % P-values < 0.05 Condition Number
1 Correlated 0.636 100 1.52e+04
2 Behavioral 0.687 100 74.4
3 Environmental 0.639 100 908
  • Although all 3 models have similar R-squared values and all predictors are statistically significant, Model 2 (Behavioral Characteristics) has the highest R-squared and the lowest condition number, indicating lower possibility of multicollinearity issues.
  • As such, based on these metrics, of these 3 regression models, the Behavioral model best accounts for the variation in the dependent variable.
  • Caveat: There may be other models combining correlated, behavioral, and environmental characteristics that are more "effective".
  • Now we'll move on to assessing the models' predictive ability.

Train and Test Splits¶

In [374]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Define variables
X1 = county_data[['LogMedianHouseholdIncome','Excessive.Drinking']]
y = county_data['Poor.Health']

# Split the data into train and test
X1_train, X1_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X1, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state=1940)

# Fit
clf = LinearRegression()
clf.fit(X1_train,y_train)

# Predict and score accuracy (%)
clf.predict(X1_test)
print(clf.score(X1_test,y_test))

0.6654120454914023
Model # Characteristics Prediction Accuracy
1 Correlated 66.54%
2 Behavioral 70.35%
3 Environmental 59.40%

The second model has the most accurate predictions, which corroborates the earlier regression metric analysis.

Tree Regression Models¶

  • As noted in the observation of the Life Expectancy variable, the relationship between a predictor and the dependent variable may vary by state.
  • This means that the relationships may not be linear or the same for each state/county, and multiple regression may not be as effective.
  • We will now examine if a predictive tree model using behavioral characteristics will better represent variation than the linear regression model specified in the last section.

R-square Comparison¶

Model/Tree # Characteristics R-square of Best Tree
1 Correlated 0.6889
2 Behavioral 0.6077
3 Environmental 0.6809
  • In this case, based on R-square, the behavioral tree performs the worst of the 3.
  • The R-square for Tree 1 here performs better than the R-square for Linear Regression Model 2 as specified in the last section.
  • A cost-complexity pruning tree with correlated predictors (Excessive Drinking and the log of Median Household Income, compared to the other analysis options presented here, accounts for more of the variation in the dependent variable than do the continuous behavioral and environmental characteristics. It also performs better than a simple tree without pruning.

Conclusions¶

  1. Excessive Drinking, the log of Median Household Income, and Life Expectancy are the predictors most strongly correlated with Poor Health.
  2. How the predictors perform in accounting for variation in health index depends on the type of regression (multiple or tree) performed.
    The correlated predictors perform best under tree regression.
    The behavioral predictors perform best under multiple regression.
    Regardless of which tree, Median Household Income is one of the most important predictors.
  3. Given multiple regression with characteristics segmented by type, the behavioral characteristics best predict health index, at an accuracy rate of 70.35%.
  4. Based on the models developed in this analysis, the best R-square is generated by a tree with cost-complexity pruning using the correlated predictors (Excessive Drinking and Median Household Income).

Suggestions for Further Analysis¶

  1. Because the R-square and prediction accuracy values generated by some of the models are quite similar, one approach would be to regenerate prediction values with different random seeds and train/test split proportions.
  2. Observing other predictors and how they vary by state may also provide insight into improving the tree models.
  3. In further analysis, addressing some of the multicollinearity between related predictors may improve prediction accuracy.
